    {
      "id": "p001",
      "index": 1,
      "source": "Apple accounted for 78% of TSMC’s non-wafer revenue in 2020. That was peak dominance. InFO was scaling for A-series chips, and CoWoS had few customers. By 2024, Apple’s share dropped to 36%. By 2025, it falls further to 30%. Apple’s absolute packaging revenue continues growing. But AI customers, led by Nvidia, are scaling CoWoS faster.",
      "source_html": null,
      "element_type": "p",
      "inline_elements": [],
      "parent_block_id": "b0328",
      "parent_block_index": 328,
      "parent_block_type": "p",
      "parent_block_markdown": "Apple accounted for 78% of TSMC’s non-wafer revenue in 2020. That was peak dominance. InFO was scaling for A-series chips, and CoWoS had few customers. By 2024, Apple’s share dropped to 36%. By 2025, it falls further to 30%. Apple’s absolute packaging revenue continues growing. But AI customers, led by Nvidia, are scaling CoWoS faster.",
      "parent_block_plain_text": "Apple accounted for 78% of TSMC’s non-wafer revenue in 2020. That was peak dominance. InFO was scaling for A-series chips, and CoWoS had few customers. By 2024, Apple’s share dropped to 36%. By 2025, it falls further to 30%. Apple’s absolute packaging revenue continues growing. But AI customers, led by Nvidia, are scaling CoWoS faster.",
      "parent_source_html": null,
      "parent_inline_elements": [],
